<h2>&#x221a;śrī1<i> 'mix'</i></h2><p>
<i>present: </i>[9.] <b>śrīṇā́ti</b> &#xa0;<b>śrīṇīté</b> &#xa0;</p><p>
<i>perfect: </i><b>śiśriye</b> &#xa0;</p><p>
<i>aorist: </i>[3.] <b>aśiśrayus</b> &#xa0;</p><p>
<i>verbal: </i><b>śrītá</b> &#xa0;<b>śīrta</b> &#xa0;<b>śrītvā</b> &#xa0;</p><p>
<i>derivatives: </i><b>-śir</b> &#xa0;<b>-śira</b> <sub>S.+ </sub>&#xa0;<b>-śrī</b> <sub>V. </sub>&#xa0;<b>śrayaṇa</b> <sub>S. </sub>&#xa0;</p><p>
Is probably only a form of &#x221a;<b>śri</b>, from which it is at some points hardly separable.  The interrelations of the roots <b>sṛ</b>, <b>śrā</b>, <b>śri</b>, <b>śrī</b> are intricate, and not yet fully worked out.  Eepecially doubtful is it what is the connection with them of the noun <b>śrī́</b> V.+ 'fortune', and the related <b>śriyás</b> RV., <b>śréyas</b> V.+, <b>śréṣṭha</b> V.+, <b>śremán</b> B.</p></body>
